{"cursor":"11042","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n.]]\n\n\nThe 'nucleolus' (plural 'nucleoli') is a non-membrane bound structure and is the\ncentre of the\ncell. [http://micro.magnet.fsu.edu/cells/nucleus/nucleolus.html Molecular\nExpressions Cell Biology: The Nucleolus]. Micro.magnet.fsu.edu (2005-05-10).\nRetrieved on 2013-03-03. It is composed of proteins and nucleic acids\nfound within the nucleus of eukaryotic cells. Its function is to transcribe\nribosomal RNA (rRNA) and assemble it within the cell.\n\nThe nucleolus ultrastructure can be visualized through an electron microscope,\nwhile the organization and dynamics can be studied through fluorescent protein\ntagging and fluorescent recovery after photobleaching (FRAP). Antibodies against\nthe PAF49 protein can also be used as a marker for the nucleolus in\nimmunofluorescence experiments. [http://www.genetex.com/PAF49-antibody-\nGTX102175.html PAF49 antibody | GeneTex Inc]. Genetex.com. Retrieved on 2013-03-\n03. Malfunction of nucleoli can be the cause for several human diseases.\nIt takes up to about 25% of the nuclear volume.\n","linknr":442,"url":"Nucleolus","recorded":1362512705,"links":66,"instances":["biology","genetics","genetics","biology"],"pdf":["http://www.lafontainelab.com/Suppl_data/Thiry_2005/S3.pdf","http://www.jic.ac.uk/staff/peter-shaw/pdfs/raska%20intrevcytol%2006.pdf"],"categories":["Organelles","Nuclear substructures"],"headings":["Structure","Function and ribosome assembly","Sequestration of proteins","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/f/f2/Edit-clear.svg/40px-Edit-clear.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/38/Diagram_human_cell_nucleus.svg/300px-Diagram_human_cell_nucleus.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/11/Animal_Cell.svg/350px-Animal_Cell.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/c